1. Switch Case Statements
A switch case statement is a multi-way branch statement that provides an alternative to long if-else-if chains. It matches an integer or character variable against a list of constant values called cases.

Syntax and Architecture
C
switch (choice) {
    case 'Y':
        // Block of code for choice 'Y'
        break;
    case 'N':
        // Block of code for choice 'N'
        break;
    default:
        // Fallback block if no cases match
        break;
}
Indentation: When writing cases, code blocks underneath the case label should be indented by 4 spaces (or one tab) for readability.

The default Case: Acts as a safety net. It automatically executes if the variable does not match any of the specified constants.

2. The break Keyword
The break keyword jumps execution entirely out of the innermost enclosing loop or switch control structure.

In Switch Cases: Failing to include a break causes execution to flow directly into subsequent cases ("fall-through" behavior), even if those case conditions are unmet.

In Loops: Used to force immediate termination of a loop based on an internal condition.

Example: In a loop iterating from 0 to 10:

C
if (i == 5) {
    break; 
}
When i reaches 5, the loop immediately aborts, printing only numbers 0 through 4.

3. The continue Keyword
The continue keyword skips the remaining statements in the current iteration of a loop and forces the program control to jump directly to the next iteration check.

Unlike break, it does not terminate the loop entirely.

Example: In a loop iterating from 0 to 10:

C
if (i == 5) {
    continue; 
}
When i equals 5, the execution line skips the print statement for that turn. The loop resumes normally for 6 through 10. The final console output contains numbers 0–4 and 6–10, explicitly omitting 5.
